Aug 7 2007 	Everything about this boutique hotel is amazing!	A hotel is very important to my husband &amp; I when we travel &amp; it was very hard choosing one in the wonderful city of San Francisco! There are so many great ones to choose from but, we didn't want to stay at one of those stuffy, 'chain' hotels. You hear the title 'boutique hotel' &amp; so many things come to mind-expensive &amp; tiny, among other things.We stayed during the week of July 15&gt;July 23, 2007.Well, I almost cancelled the reservation solely on the fact that this one was 5 'easy' blocks from any cable car stop. There is no 'easy' in San Francisco! But, I was reassured that this was a great place by a few forum members on various travel websites. AND, there was only one review by one of them. This member gave it a 5 out of 5 rating. Very deserving!Wellllll, I am SO glad I didn't cancel! EVERYthing about this place was truly elegant! There are only 5 floors &amp; you feel like you have booked a hotel that should rate a $400 a nite price! We paid $153 per nite!From the moment you walk into the marble foryer &amp; up the marble steps to the front desk, there is always someone there to greet you with a smile! You truly feel you are coming back to old friends! You park your car in front, they help you with your bags, then take your car to park it. $20 per day with 24 hour in/out privileges! This is an amazingly low price considering that lesser hotels were charging upwards of $35&gt;$45! You always park in front &amp; they park it for you, no matter the time of day or nite.You check in &amp; they take your bags up to your room for you.The elevator is gorgeous! AND quick! The doors even stay open for what seems to be an eternity so you have ample time(&amp; then some!)to get your luggage on/off.We were on the 4th floor &amp; our room was directly across from the elevator, which made it nice! We didn't even notice any noise because A)it isn't a child friendly hotel in my opinion, so, it is only adults using it &amp; B)our suite had a nice 'hallway' before you actually get to the living areas.The ice machine was in a nice little closet right next door to us. Again-no noise! The closet door was just like the doors to the rooms, so it blended into the asthetics very well!There is a nice sitting area, actually 3, in the lobby area. One was across from the elevator &amp; near the bar &amp; restaurant. The second was to the right of the front desk as you entered &amp; the third was up a couple of steps from the second. There is one perk that I think is so great! They have a nice computer with FREE, yes, that be FREE!, internet access! No, not 'hook your laptop up to it' access. NO! An actual computer that you can use anytime you want! There was never a line, either. I did have to wait a few minutes one time, but, I didn't mind. I was able to check my email from there &amp; that made it so much easier when I got home! Also, I was able to check-in online for our flight home &amp; print out our boarding passes! I just deleted the browser history, just in case. I wasn't worried, but you never know. Our room was so gorgeous! It was a 1 bedroom suite &amp; the bathroom was HUGE! It had double vanities with drawers &amp; cabinets! There was a mini fridge also under the middle area of the vanity. There were robes for us to wear during our stay. The bathtub/shower was set in marble &amp; had a very wide area at the back for our toiletries. There was a window that opened in the shower &amp; I wanted to hang out the window(clothed, of course!)&amp; yell out 'HEY, PIEZON!' Just a weird thing I have always wanted to do! The living room-yes, ROOM! Not 'living area', but ROOM! was huge! There was a big screen tv, fireplace(didn't work for some reason), sofa, 2 end tables, coffee table, chair by the fireplace &amp; a table with 2 chairs in the bay window area. There were 3 windows in the bay window area &amp; they actually opened. The bathroom window &amp; bay windows had no screens. We only had 4 flies in the whole room at once &amp; they kind of hung around together in the middle of the living room! Never once buzzed around us! There was always a nice breeze!Our bedroom was very large! There was the king size bed, gorgeous antique chest with a tv on it, 2 nitestands &amp; 2 closets.The bed had a partial canopy with 2 lamps for reading on the headboard above the pillows. There were bed curtains that were tied back. So cool!The bed slept verrrry comfy!Every day when they came into make your bed, they would turn it down for you &amp; leave 2 cookies wrapped with the Hotel Majestic logo on the sticker. They were so good! A very nice touch!It is a bit loud there, but HEY! It is San Francisco &amp; also a large city! The trash trucks get a very early start, but the nite is relatively quiet!We had drinks in the hotel bar almost every nite &amp; it is a small, quaint bar. Just a few tables &amp; a nice size bar to sit at. I believe the bartenders name we had was John. I am not sure. He is bald-headed. We wanted to try something different &amp; he accommodated us very nicely. He made me a drink &amp; told me if I didn't like it he would make me a different one, no charge for the one I didn't like. But, he is good at what he does &amp; I was sooo happy with that drink he made!The hotel restaurant-'Cafe Majestic' had just recently been written up in a local paper &amp; the very harsh food critic raved about it &amp; gave it 3 stars. They were ecstatic! It is very deserving! We made reservations for one of our nites there &amp; they always make sure they can get their guests staying at the hotel in no matter what. The service was exquisite &amp; the food sooooooo good! It is an upscale restaurant with down to earth prices! Their most expensive entree on the menu was $29! It isn't 'a la carte' either!The appetizers are nicely priced, as well. Salads aren't included in the meal, but, you don't really need one because you don't even miss it! They have something for vegetarians, too! The desserts are amazing! Large enuff to share, if you can stand to share them!!! We didn't feel rushed &amp; the waitress came at perfect times. My husband ordered lamb &amp; it wasn't quite cooked long enuff &amp; he wasn't going to say anything but about 5 seconds later(great timing!)the manager came around asking if everyones' meal was cooked to their liking &amp; I told him my husbands' wasn't quite done enuff &amp; he apologized &amp; whisked it off &amp; within 5 minutes, it was back &amp; perfect! Again, he apologized &amp; made the experience so great! We weren't upset. We don't get that way. The hotel has lots of pamphlets &amp; magazines for you to take to help you plan your time there &amp; to help you get around. There is a map they provide that we found to be about the best map around!It shows you where the hotel is located on the map &amp; just about anywhere you want to go(streets, that is)is on there. We found out that we were just across the street from a bus stop &amp; there was another one about 2 blocks away. But, the second one I mentioned takes its own, precious time getting there! We purchased the MUNI passes for unlimited travel on the cable cars, busses &amp; street cars &amp; they came in soooo handy! This was just one of the best hotels we could have stayed at. If we ever come back to San Francisco, I won't even bother looking for other hotels. Hotel Majestic is about the best for the money!Remember that there is tax on the parking rate &amp; it was $22.80 per day with the tax. I do have to tell you that the people of San Francisco &amp; all of Northern California are some of the nicest people you will ever want to meet! We always hear how rude Californians are &amp; that couldn't be further from the truth! We only met 3 rude, obnoxious, loud-mouthed people during our entire 2 week stay. Wanna know where they were from? New York? Noooo. LA?Noooo. MISSOURI! As a matter of fact, they live 40 minutes from us!!! That is sad to know that! There is a girl that works at the front desk of Hotel Majestic, named Nisi(KNEE-see)&amp; she was so helpful. She lives in San Francisco in an area we were trying to get to &amp; she gave us great advice on which busses to take &amp; we had no trouble at all!I do have to tell you about something that seals my wonderful opinion about San Franciscans. My husband turned 50 while we were staying in San Francisco. 2 days before his birthday, we were in the bar relaxing with a drink.This couple walked in &amp; sat at a table next to ours. We got to talking to them &amp; found out that he is a lawyer &amp; his wife is from Ireland. We talked about many things &amp; one was how we love England &amp; when we stayed there I found this wonderful thing called canned figs. Kind of like canned peaches. That concept. I cannot find them ANYwhere. So, we talked for a while longer &amp; then, they had to go. Such a nice couple. Welll, the next evening when we returned from our day out, our room phone rang. The front desk told me there was a package for us at the front desk. Ok, I thought our daughter or my mother had sent him something because of his 50th birthday. We went down &amp; there was a white bag with handles with a card addressed to us. It was from the lawyer &amp; his wife whom we had only met the evening before &amp; talked for only an hour or so!!! The card had such a nice note written &amp; they welcomed us to their city &amp; told us to have a drink on his birthday on them! There was a bottle of Mumm Napa Sparkling Wine &amp; 2 jars of figs!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!! That was by far THE nicest thing ANYone could ever do for someone, let alone perfect strangers!That made my husbands birthday just that more special!So, don't let anyone tell you these people are rude. They are some of the nicest people we have ever met!This is a great hotel &amp; I think I like the boutique hotels better because it is more intimate &amp; they know you &amp; greet you like an old friend. If you want a nice place to stay-Hotel Majestic fits the bill. I don't know about the regular room or Junior Suite, but I can tell you that you can't go wrong staying here! I am going to put as many photos as I can on here. Some of them aren't perfect, but, you can at least tell how nice the whole hotel is.Happy Travels!PS-Pix will be coming later. Some need to be 'uprighted'.	
Jul 25 2007 	Charming and Enjoyable	Our family stayed at Hotel Majestic the last week of June. We are two adults with two teenagers. We didn't want to spend tons of money, but wanted a nice hotel with charm and character. We thought this hotel fit the bill perfectly. It was centrally located in the city- we were able to walk to Chinatown, and also to Union Square, and the piers were not to far away at all. The front desk people were very helpful and friendly. The room we had was a suite and there was plenty of room for the 4 of us. The furnishings and bathroom tiles were Victorian style and very pretty. There were qirks in the room (the floor on the way to the bathroom was gently sloping, for instance), but that just added to the fun of staying in an older hotel. And there were beautiful details and touches- like the chandelier light fixtures and the fluffy bathrobes they provided. I thought the hotel was a great choice and we would stay there again if we were in town.	
