Dec 1 2004	Very Poor	I'm sorry but I had real problems when I checked into this hotel. First of all they had promised me that I would have this beautiful room to surprise my wife with. Well she was surprised when she found out how small the room was. We also read that they had one of the nicest restaurants in San Francisco. Unfortunately, that has been closed for two years. The staff there seemed too busy planning for an outing that night than helping us with questions about the city. I'm really trying not to stay only bad things, but unfortunately the hotel is honestly not very good at any price.	
Nov 2 2004	choose majestic if you want old-world elegance	me and my boyfriend stayed at the majestic for two nights in august 2004 as the last stop of our california roadtrip. we loved it. the room was tiny but very cozy with a canopy bed that looked like one from a european castle (and boy was it comfy!). the room was 139 a night in high tourist season including breakfast - a slightly expanded continental which is the prevalent norm in california. the bathroom was very nice and the fluffy bathrobes were excellent. the so-called wine tasting hour with hors d'ouvres was an overstatement but we got an umbrella and great recommendations for dinner instead. it is two blocks from the cable car line - very convenient to all the touristy stuff. we would definitely stay there again - i would recommend it for a romantic getaway. if you plan to stay inside for most of the weekend, get a king size room or a suite - the queen ones are not up to american standards.	
Oct 25 2004	Fantastic Stay	We stayed at the Majetic from the 15th September - 22nd September and had a fantastic time. Room was great, staff were very friendly and helpful. Found the hotel a good location for many of the places we wanted to visit and was only a 15 minute walk to Union Square and only a 25 minute walk to Fisherman Wharf if you wanted to walk. Cookies on the bed at night were a real treat and we managed to get two packs a day! Next time we come back to San Francisco we will definitely stay there again.	
Sep 21 2004	San Francisco's best-kept secret	The Majestic is a great hotel for the price. In the past in San Francisco, I've always stayed in the downtown area, which has meant choosing between cheap &amp; awful or superb but costly. The Majestic is a bit out of the way (at Sutter &amp; Gough), but it was a quick cab ride from everywhere. The rooms were spotless and beautifully decorated, the staff was excellent and knew its business, and the hotel even provided a nice complimentary breakfast in a sunny dining room every day. All this and it wasn't even expensive. From now on I'm definitely staying at the Majestic.	
Aug 11 2004	Beautiful...a little out of the way and possible mold in the bath	The hotel was beautiful, the staff was pleasant and I was happy to be there. It is out of the way to go to the typical tourist attractions- you need to take public transit, which is manageable and not far away once you figure it out. If you want to walk out of your door and go to dinner, it's about 5 blocks to where they recommend restaurants although it's a quiet residential walk.A typical problem with old buildings is mold in the bathroom- that was the case in the first room that we stayed in. It had a canapy bed, exquisite wallpaper and mold in the tub. I asked at the front desk if they would clean it out and they were very apologetic and assurred me that it would be taken care of when I returned as I was on my way out. We came in late and went to bed and the next morning when I hopped in the shower the mold was still there. I went to the desk and after being sent to a replacement room that was ugly, off the staircase and dreary, I went back to the desk near tears. They explained that they couldn't upgrade me because they had only one suite left and gave me the choice of two other rooms. I chose one that was on the side of the hotel and didn't have much light, but did have a clean bathroom. It worked for us and I was happy with the switch.	
